  volume = {61},
  abstract = {The species-confidence hypothesis asserts that birds prefer mates\$$\backslash$backslash\$nwhose colors match those of their species and avoid potential mates\$$\backslash$backslash\$nwhose colors are atypical of conspecifics. Earlier point-count research\$$\backslash$backslash\$nindicated this mate-choice hypothesis also may explain avian reactions\$$\backslash$backslash\$nto observer clothing color. In central Texas, during January and\$$\backslash$backslash\$nFebruary 1993, we tested further whether the species-confidence hypothesis\$$\backslash$backslash\$nholds for reactions to observer clothing color by determining how\$$\backslash$backslash\$nclose an investigator could get to individuals before they flushed\$$\backslash$backslash\$n(approach distance) and how long individuals remained visible near\$$\backslash$backslash\$ntheir initial flush point (detectability period). The same investigator\$$\backslash$backslash\$nexperimentally wore or did not wear a hunter-orange vest, which some\$$\backslash$backslash\$nwildlife biologists wear as a safety precaution during hunting-season\$$\backslash$backslash\$nfield studies. The vest did not affect approach distance for species\$$\backslash$backslash\$nwith red or orange on their bodies (American robin \$$\backslash$backslash\$textit\{[Turdus\$$\backslash$backslash\$nmigratorius]\}, P = 0.247; northern cardinal \$$\backslash$backslash\$textit\{[Cardinalis cardinalis]\},\$$\backslash$backslash\$nP = 0.196: ruby-crowned kinglet \$$\backslash$backslash\$textit\{[Regulus calendula]\}, P =\$$\backslash$backslash\$n0.434; red-bellied woodpecker \$$\backslash$backslash\$textit\{[Melanerpes carolinus]\}, P\$$\backslash$backslash\$n= 0.113). In contrast, approach distances for species without red\$$\backslash$backslash\$nor orange were longer when the vest was worn than when it was not\$$\backslash$backslash\$nworn (Carolina chickadee \$$\backslash$backslash\$textit\{[Parus carolinensis]\}, P = 0.032;\$$\backslash$backslash\$nnorthern mockingbird \$$\backslash$backslash\$textit\{[Mimus polyglottos]\}, P = 0.033; yellow-rumped\$$\backslash$backslash\$nwarbler \$$\backslash$backslash\$textit\{[Dendroica coronata]\}, P = 0.001). Differences in\$$\backslash$backslash\$ndetectability period between vest conditions depended on air temperature\$$\backslash$backslash\$nfor American robins (P = 0.003) and on the variation in visibility\$$\backslash$backslash\$nwithin habitats for northern cardinals (P $\backslash$textless 0.001). Detectability\$$\backslash$backslash\$nperiod was shorter when the vest was worn than when it was not worn\$$\backslash$backslash\$nfor Carolina chickadees (P = 0.057) and yellow-rumped warblers (P\$$\backslash$backslash\$n= 0.060). Thus, for several species this matechoice hypothesis seems\$$\backslash$backslash\$nto apply to garment color as well. Some species' reactions demonstrated\$$\backslash$backslash\$nthat, if birds respond significantly to clothing color, important\$$\backslash$backslash\$nassumptions of distance-sampling techniques used to estimate avian\$$\backslash$backslash\$nrichness, density, and abundance will be violated, and these parameters\$$\backslash$backslash\$nwill be underestimated. Wildlife scientists will be more likely to\$$\backslash$backslash\$ndraw valid inferences and recommend effective management practices\$$\backslash$backslash\$nfrom avian data gathered via distance-sampling methods if reactions\$$\backslash$backslash\$nto clothing color are precluded.},
